snippet.textDisplay: Interesting comments when comparing Deadpool. We're basically siding with a psycho - he slices a guy open from chest to sphincter by jumping on the katana he just stuck through him. He talks constantly through the movie but switching between dialog and fourth-wall monologue is so smooth you don't even notice. There's a constant switching back and forth over long periods to tell DP's excellent origin story. And there's little character building, except for DP - what did we really learn about Colossus or NTW or the villains? They are just there to further DP's strong story and reflect his wit, yet they are brilliant characters without trying hard. Same idea as Harley but in the Marvel universe, everything just works. Disappointed to hear there was so little of the actual Birds and the line-up because the comics were surprisingly good.

snippet.textDisplay:
Dam.
I loved the crap out of this movie! What the fuck is wrong with people? I don’t want to blame the audience, as I’m right there with them, but idk how this quacked.
I look forward to whatever Margo Robbie does next, and wish her all the success ever! Ewan Mcgregor and the whole cast and everyone did amazing.
Harleyquinn is over the dam top, and unrelatable to audiences perhaps?
Beyond the Trailer said all the guys were assholes, except one dude, and he still sold her out.
Perhaps this movie lacked a “straight man”, where there was some sense of contrast, and also there was anything relatable with broad appeal? Harleyquinn was her own straight man. She had a PHD in psychology and could break down someone’s motives and everything, but she was mostly also her own crazy person. The more I think about it, it didn’t have contrast. It kept moving the goal posts as needed. It was free form, and very fun, but I’m not sure anyone learned anything.
Marvel has lots of straight arrows. They set the tempo, or at least a baseline only to throw it all the way out sometimes.
Jaqaline Phoenix “the joker” took a lot of time building up a baseline, and “was a man of the ppl” another review said.
Mayhaps if this movie jumped between Harleyquinn as a Psychiatrist, then back to her now? Idk. That could have been mind blowing, and audience gets to know her, and love her as a person would be freaking amazing. I’d watch Margo eat a ham sandwich at a diner, and bullshit about her favorite dress or some shit.

Margo Robbie was amazing in that bit where she explains financial cabal in a hot tub w wine, I saw a couple movies just because she was in it. Idk
Idfk why it flopped

snippet.textDisplay:
I think what I enjoyed most about the movie was that it was very unpretentious; it set out to be fun and colourful and bombastic, and not exactly deep or Oscar-winning material. Some might call that shallow, but I think it was more a case of Margot Robbie and the crew behind it knowing exactly what the audience wanted. Similar to old Arnie movies, its fun to just turn your brain off, sit back with popcorn, and enjoy the mayhem.


Compare to, say, Batman vs Superman, which tried to take the material seriously. Or Justice League, for trying to ape Avengers/Marvel. Birds of Prey is just an enjoyable romp and doesn't have any aspirations of being anything else, and that's why it works really well. Could it be stronger? Of course. Was it bad? Not at all.

snippet.textDisplay: I think you just oversimplified and reduced the film down massively underestimating that they did give a moment of reasoning for Black Mask being an asshole. It’s the scene where he’s trying to sway someone to bring his associates into the fold. Yes, there are a few characters that don’t get much if any characterization, but with a cast and a limited time as it has to tell the story in the frantic pace as such is expected. There’s enough information and scenes that do make you side with them. Montoya is the detective that is used by other men on the force for their benefit. Black Canary knows the price of fighting crime because of her mother and chooses to hide, but has a crisis of conscience when a little girl, who has parents that are aggressive and possibly violent toward one another which Cassandra’s way of escape is pickpocketing. While Huntress is mostly vacant and emotionless, her backstory expresses her numbness, but she warms up when she has something to fight for that isn’t revenge. Sometimes, I think we see different movies. As for Joker, my issues are because of the exploitation’s and glorification of a mentally ill person’s delusions. Yes, Deadpool and Harley Quinn are terrible Murders, but these movies are not serious and often silly. Joker was extremely serious and during a time where mass shooters’ excuse, by the media, is that they are mentally ill. Also, Joker is just wishy washy on everything. Aspects of bigger picture issues are established but don’t really mean anything because the movie being told through the eyes of the central character. I don’t think that the narration was excessive at all in Birds of Prey. It kept a consistent style and voice. I think you overthink this rather than a movie like Joker when this just fun, dark comedy that was generated by the likes that Deadpool brought. Tone and storytelling do alter how a movie is received. I thought this was a fun movie. It’s not gunning for Oscars, but it has a fresh spirit about it that makes it great to watch again, not punishing.
